param.dialogReference: Additional height added to the surface elevation of the Targets. The default is 0.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.dialogReference: Input raster surface on which calculations are based.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Line_Of_Sight_Features
param.dialogReference: Output Line Of Sight features of visible and non-visible surface areas.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Sight_Line_Features
param.dialogReference: A two-point line between observer point and target point. Unlike the Output Line Of Sight, this does not follow the surface terrain. This is useful in a 3D scene to see the straight line of sight between observer and target.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Observer_Features
param.dialogReference: Input observer features colored if the targets are visible (green) or not visible (red).
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Output_Target_Features
param.dialogReference: Output Target features show what is visible to the observers (green) or not (red).
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

param.name: Input_Obstruction_Features
param.dialogReference: A feature class of multipatches which may obstruct the line(s) of sight. Optionally, select a 3D feature layer. IMPORTANT: If Input Obstruction Features are used, the resulting Output Linear Line Of Sight features are different. The resulting lines do not follow the surface profile, but extend directly between observer and target. This drastically changes the profile graph of the features from Attach Profile Graph To LLOS.
param.pythonReference: There is no python reference for this parameter.

tool.summary: Creates line(s) of sight between observers and targets.
tool.usage:
• This tool requires 3D Analyst.

  • Linear Line Of Sight (LLOS) uses Constuct Sight Lines and Line Of Sight from 3D Analyst.

  • The observer is the start point, and the target is the endpoint of the line used to determine visibility.

  • Uses one or more observers and one or more target point features.

  • All observers are matched with all targets.

  • Resulting line(s) is colored to show visible sections (green) and non-visible sections (red).

  • The TarIsVis field of the Output Line Of Sight Features determines if the target is visible (1) or not visible (0) to the observer.

  • The VisCode field of the Output Line Of Sight Features determines if the surface segment is visible (1) to the observer or is not visible (2).

  • The line attribute TarIsVis tells if a target is visible to an observer: 0 is NOT visible and 1 is visible.

  • OID_OBSERV and OID_TARGET are the object IDs of the observer point and target point used to create the line of sight.

  • Output LLOS attributes ObsZ and TgtZ are the elevations of the observer and target points.

  • This tool uses earth curvature and refractivity calculations if the Input Surface supports it.

  • Units of the heights are the units of the elevation surface.
